50|$|A legal lien, in many {{common law}} systems, {{includes}} {{a right to}} retain physical possession of tangible assets as security for the underlying obligations. In some jurisdictions it {{is a form of}} possessory security, and possession of the assets must be transferred to (and maintained by) the secured party. In the case of a <b>possessory</b> <b>lien,</b> the right is purely passive. In the case of a <b>possessory</b> <b>lien,</b> the secured party (the lienor) has no right to sell the assets - merely a right to refuse to return them until paid. In the United States, a lien can be a non-possessory security interest.|$|E
